ce:section.ce:para:
Recently, Yang et al. [15] have reported that the oxygen-deficient TiO2/graphene symmetric supercapacitor showed a higher energy density (14.1 Wh/kg) and a power density (8.5 kW/kg). Xiang et al. have prepared the rGO-TiO2 hybrid electrodes for better super capacitance performance with varying composite ratio of 9:1, 7:3, and 5:5 (rGO: TiO2). In this, the 7:3 ratio of rGO: TiO2 shows the better supercapacitive behavior against Na2SO4 electrolyte. The unique shape of TiO2 nanobelts assist to improve the large surface area which supports to enhance charge transport property of the electrode and they reported the specific capacitance of 225 F/g at the charge current density of 0.125 A/g [16]. Sundriyal et al. have prepared the 2D structured rGO/TiO2 electrode by hydrothermal method and H2SO4 have been taken as an electrolyte solution. The specific capacitance obtained about 233.67 F/g at a current density of 1 A/g. In this, rGO helps to decrease the series resistance and improves the ionic diffusion rate of TiO2 
                     [17]. Heng et al. have prepared the rGO/TiO2 anode material and activated carbon as a cathode material and KOH took as an electrolyte solution. The different weight percentage such as 5, 10, 20 and 30 wt. % of rGO has been loaded into TiO2. 10 wt. % was measured as an optimum loading and the specific capacity achieved at 331 mAh/g at a scan rate of 30 mV/s. It reported that the enhanced performance is due to the hierarchical structure of the electrode and large surface area which improves the ion diffusion rate and rGO helps to improve the electron transfer [18]. Saravath et al. have prepared the N-doped TiO2/N-doped graphene electrode by hydrothermal method for supercapacitor application and Na2SO4 was used as an electrolyte solution. Doping of nitrogen facilitates the improvement of the electronic conductivity of TiO2/rGO and the specific capacitance value was obtained at 205.1 F/g at the scan rate of 1 mV/s [19]. Liu et al. have prepared the rice-like structured TiO2/graphene aerogel by hydrothermal method for supercapacitor application and H2SO4 has been taken as an electrolyte solution. They have obtained the specific capacitance value of 372.3 F/g at a current density of 0.2 A/g. The excellent performance of the electrode is due to the (i) unique rice-like structured TiO2 which improves the pseudocapacitive behavior and surface area (ii) macroporous graphene conveniences the electron transport, (iii) covalent bonding of TiO2 with graphene [20]. These works conclude that hydrothermal method is a simple and cost-effective approach. Based on these, we have also adopted the hydrothermal method to prepare TiO2/carbon allotrope nanohybrids for supercapacitor application. In order to maintain the composition proportion (10:1) in the hybrid system, the prepared TiO2 anatase nanoparticles (100 mg) were mixed with GO (10 mg)/MWCNT (10 mg) and autoclaved at 120 °C for 12 h which is used for the energy storage investigation. The obtained results were compared with the recent TiO2/Graphene-based composite materials (Table 1
                     ) [19–26]. This comparison shows that our TiO2/rGO hybrid electrode shows the excellent performance (558 F/g at 1 A/g) compared with the above reported works.
